# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2006-uk-independence-party-leadership-election] The UK Independence Party (UKIP) held a leadership election in September 2006.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2006-uk-independence-party-leadership-election] The Eurosceptic party had been led since 2002 by Roger Knapman.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2006-uk-independence-party-leadership-election] Although he was entitled to stand for second term of office on the expiry of his four-year term, he decided not to.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2006-uk-independence-party-leadership-election] Farage was elected, with 44% of the votes cast.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A referendum on Scottish independence from the United Kingdom was held in Scotland on 18 September 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The referendum question was "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which voters answered with "Yes" or "No".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The turnout of 84.6% was the highest recorded for an election or referendum in the United Kingdom since the January 1910 general election, which was held before the introduction of universal suffrage.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 set out the arrangements for the referendum and was passed by the Scottish Parliament in November 2013, following an agreement between the devolved Scottish government and the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The independence proposal required a simple majority to pass.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] All European Union (EU) or Commonwealth citizens residing in Scotland age 16 or over could vote, with some exceptions, which produced a total electorate of almost 4,300,000 people.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was the first time that the electoral franchise was extended to include 16- and 17-year-olds in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Yes Scotland was the main campaign group for independence, while Better Together was the main campaign group in favour of maintaining the union.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Many other campaign groups, political parties, businesses, newspapers, and prominent individuals were also involved.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Prominent issues raised during the referendum included what currency an independent Scotland would use, public expenditure, EU membership, and North Sea oil.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An exit poll revealed that retention of the pound sterling was the deciding factor for those who voted No, while "disaffection with Westminster politics" was the deciding factor for those who voted Yes.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England were established as independent countries during the Middle Ages.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After fighting a series of wars during the 14th century, the two monarchies entered a personal union in 1603 (the Union of the Crowns) when James VI of Scotland also became James I of England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two nations were temporarily united under one government when Oliver Cromwell was declared Lord Protector of a Commonwealth in 1653, but this was dissolved when the monarchy was restored in 1660.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Scotland and England united to form the Kingdom of Great Britain in 1707 (Wales had already been unilaterally incorporated into England in the mid-16th century).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scots favoured union to solve the economic problems caused by the failure of the Darien scheme and the English favoured it to secure the Hanoverian line of succession.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Great Britain in turn united with the Kingdom of Ireland in 1801, forming the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Most of Ireland left the Union in 1922 to form the Irish Free State; consequently, the full name of the United Kingdom since 1927 is the *United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Labour Party was committed to home rule for Scotland in the 1920s, but it slipped down its agenda in the following years.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish National Party (SNP) was founded in 1934, but did not achieve significant electoral success until the 1960s.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A petition calling for home rule, the Scottish Covenant, was signed by 2,000,000 people (out of a population of 5,000,000) in the late 1940s.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As James Callaghan's Labour Government of the late 1970s was pressured by the SNP, Scottish devolution was, for the first time, seriously proposed.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In a 1979 referendum for a devolved Scottish Assembly, a narrow majority of votes were cast in favour of devolution, but this had no effect due to a requirement that the number voting 'Yes' had to exceed 40% of the total electorate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] No further constitutional reform was proposed until Labour returned to power in a landslide electoral victory in May 1997.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A second Scottish devolution referendum was held later that year, as promised in the Labour election manifesto.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Clear majorities expressed support for both a devolved Scottish Parliament (74.3% in favour) and that Parliament having the power to vary the basic rate of UK income tax (63.5% in favour).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scotland Act 1998 established the new Scottish Parliament, first elected on 6 May 1999, with power to legislate on unreserved matters within Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A commitment to hold an independence referendum in 2010 was part of the SNP's election manifesto when it contested the 2007 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The press were largely hostile towards the SNP, with a headline for *The Scottish Sun* in May 2007 stating – beside an image of a hangman's noose – "Vote SNP today and you put Scotland's head in the noose".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As a result of that election, the SNP became the largest party in the Scottish Parliament and formed a minority government led by the First Minister, Alex Salmond.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP administration launched a 'National Conversation' as a consultation exercise in August 2007, part of which included a draft referendum bill, the *Referendum (Scotland) Bill*.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After this, a white paper for the proposed Referendum Bill was published, on 30 November 2009.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It detailed four possible scenarios, with the text of the Bill and Referendum to be revealed later.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The scenarios were: no change; devolution per the Calman Review; further devolution; and full independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government published a draft version of the bill on 25 February 2010 for public consultation; *Scotland's Future: Draft Referendum (Scotland) Bill Consultation Paper* contained a consultation document and a draft version of the bill.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The consultation paper set out the proposed ballot papers, the mechanics of the proposed referendum, and how the proposed referendum was to be regulated.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The third proposal was for full independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 3rd Scottish Parliament only 50 of 129 MSPs (47 SNP, 2 Greens, and Margo MacDonald) supported a referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government withdrew the bill in September 2010 after failing to secure opposition support.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP repeated its commitment to hold an independence referendum when it published its manifesto for the 2011 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Days before the election, Salmond said that legislation for a referendum would be proposed in the "second half of the parliament", as he wanted to secure more powers for the Scottish Parliament via the Scotland Bill first.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the election, the SNP won 69 of the 129 seats, securing a majority in a proportional representative voting system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] UK Prime Minister David Cameron congratulated Salmond on his 'emphatic win', but pledged to campaign for the Union if the SNP carried out their pledge to hold a referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, the UK government offered to legislate to provide the Scottish Parliament with the powers to hold a referendum, providing it was 'fair, legal and decisive'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This would set 'terms of reference for the referendum', such as its question(s), elector eligibility, and which body would organise the vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As the UK government worked on legal details, including the timing of the vote, Salmond announced an intention to hold the referendum in the autumn of 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Negotiations continued between the two governments until October 2012, when the Edinburgh Agreement was reached.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum (Franchise) Act 2013 was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 27 June 2013 and received Royal Assent on 7 August 2013.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 26 November 2013, the Scottish government published *Scotland's Future*, a 670-page white paper laying out the case for independence and the means by which Scotland might become an independent country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Government announced on 21 March 2013 that the referendum would be held on Thursday 18 September 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Some media reports mentioned that 2014 would be the 700th anniversary of the Battle of Bannockburn and that Scotland would also host the 2014 Commonwealth Games and the 2014 Ryder Cup.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond agreed that the presence of these events made 2014 a "good year to hold a referendum".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Convicted prisoners were not able to vote in the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) had ruled that this restriction was unlawful, but Scottish judge Lord Glennie said that he believed the ECHR judgment would apply only to parliamentary elections.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Appeals against his ruling were rejected by the Court of Session in Edinburgh and the UK Supreme Court.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The normal voting age was reduced from 18 to 16 for the referendum, as it was a Scottish National Party policy to reduce the voting age for all elections in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The move was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Greens.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, Labour MSP Elaine Murray led a debate arguing that the franchise should be extended to Scots living outside Scotland, including the approximately 800,000 living in the other parts of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the House of Lords, Baroness Symons argued that the rest of the UK should be allowed to vote on Scottish independence because it would affect the whole country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This argument was rejected by the UK government, as the Advocate General for Scotland Lord Wallace said that "whether or not Scotland should leave the United Kingdom is a matter for Scotland".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Wallace also pointed to the fact that only two of 11 referendums since 1973 had been across all of the United Kingdom.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Professor John Curtice cited the precedent of the 1973 Northern Ireland sovereignty referendum (the "border poll"), which allowed only those resident in a part of the UK to vote on its sovereignty.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was debate as to whether the Scottish Parliament had the power to legislate for a referendum relating to the issue of Scottish independence, as the constitution is a matter reserved to the UK Parliament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government insisted in 2010 that they could legislate for a referendum, as it would be an "advisory referendum on extending the powers of the Scottish Parliament", whose result would "have no legal effect on the Union".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Lord Wallace, Advocate General for Scotland, said in January 2012 that holding a referendum concerning the constitution would be outside the legislative power of the Scottish Parliament and that private individuals could challenge a Scottish Parliament referendum bill.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two governments signed the Edinburgh Agreement, which allowed for the temporary transfer of legal authority.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Per the Edinburgh Agreement, the UK government drafted an Order in Council granting the Scottish Parliament the necessary powers to hold, on or before 31 December 2014, an independence referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The draft Order was approved by resolutions of both Houses of Parliament, and the Order ("The Scotland Act 1998 (Modification of Schedule 5) Order 2013"), was approved by Queen Elizabeth II at a meeting of the Privy Council on 12 February 2013.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under the powers temporarily transferred from Westminster under the section 30 Order, the Scottish Parliament adopted the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Act was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 14 November 2013 and received Royal Assent on 17 December 2013.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under section 36 of the Act, it came into force the day after Royal Assent.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission was responsible for overseeing the referendum, "with the exception of the conduct of the poll and announcement of the result, and the giving of grants.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In its role of regulating the campaign and campaign spending, the Electoral Commission will report to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] (...) The poll and count will be managed in the same way as [local] elections, by local returning officers (...) and directed by a Chief Counting Officer".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Edinburgh Agreement stated that the wording of the question would be decided by the Scottish Parliament and reviewed for intelligibility by the Electoral Commission.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government stated that its preferred question was "Do you agree that Scotland should be an independent country?" The Electoral Commission tested the proposed question along with three other possible versions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Their research found that the "Do you agree" preface made it a leading question, which would be more likely to garner a positive response.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The question was amended to "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which the Electoral Commission found was the most neutral and concise of the versions tested.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 2010 Draft Bill, the Scottish government proposed that there would be one designated campaign organisation for each outcome, both of which would be permitted to spend up to £750,000 on their campaign and to send one free mailshot to every household or voter in the referendum franchise.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was to be no public funding for campaigns.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Registered political parties were each to be allowed to spend £100,000.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This proposed limit on party spending was increased to £250,000 in 2012.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In 2013, new proposals by the Electoral Commission for the 16-week regulated period preceding the poll were accepted.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] They allowed the two designated campaign organisations to spend up to £1.5 million each and for the parties in Scotland to spend the following amounts: £1,344,000 (SNP); £834,000 (Labour); £396,000 (Conservatives); £201,000 (Liberal Democrats); £150,000 (Greens).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An unlimited number of other organisations could register with the Electoral Commission, but their spending was limited to £150,000.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Groups spending more than £250,000 were required to submit audited returns to the Commission by 18 March 2015.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] According to the Scottish government's consultation paper published on 25 February 2010, the cost of the referendum was "likely to be around £9.5 million", mostly spent on running the poll and the count.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Costs would also include the posting of one neutral information leaflet about the referendum to every Scottish household, and one free mailshot to every household or voter in the poll for the designated campaign organisations.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In April 2013, the projected cost of the referendum was £13.3 million; the final administrative cost was £15.85 million.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scottish independence, Yes Scotland, was launched on 25 May 2012.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Its chief executive was Blair Jenkins, formerly the Director of Broadcasting at STV and Head of News and Current Affairs at both STV and BBC Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign was supported by the SNP, the Scottish Green Party (which also created "its own pro-independence campaign to run alongside Yes Scotland") and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] At its launch, Salmond stated that he hoped one million people in Scotland would sign a declaration of support for independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 22 August 2014, Yes Scotland announced that the one million target had been surpassed.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scotland remaining in the UK, Better Together, was launched on 25 June 2012.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was led by Alistair Darling, former Chancellor of the Exchequer, and had support from the Conservative Party, Labour Party and Liberal Democrats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Political advertising on television and radio in the UK was prohibited by the Communications Act 2003, with the exception of permitted party political broadcasts.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Three major cinema chains stopped showing adverts by referendum campaign groups after receiving negative feedback from their customers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In December 2013, the Better Together campaign declared that it had received donations of £2,800,000.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Six-figure contributions were made by businessmen Ian Taylor and Donald Houston, and by author C.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Almost 27,000 donations of under £7,500 had been received by the same date.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Rowling, who announced in June 2014 that she had given £1,000,000 to the Better Together campaign.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the following month, whisky distiller William Grant & Sons announced a donation of approximately £100,000.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 12 August 2014, Better Together announced that it had raised enough money to cover the maximum spending permitted and was no longer accepting donations.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was attributed in part to a large number of small donations being received after the first televised debate between First Minister Alex Salmond and Labour MP Alistair Darling.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of May 2014, the Yes Scotland campaign had declared £4,500,000 in cash donations.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] EuroMillions lottery-winners Chris and Colin Weir gave £3,500,000.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A six-figure donation was given by investment fund manager Angus Tulloch; approximately 18,000 donations of less than £7,500 had been made by the same date.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Voting for the referendum commenced on 27 August 2014, with the receipt of ballots by postal voters.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of 15 August, 680,235 eligible voters had registered for postal voting, a 20% increase compared with March 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] During the postal vote phase, Police Scotland arrested a man from Glasgow on suspicion of selling his vote on eBay.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The registration deadline for referendum voters was 2 September 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Several councils reported the processing of "unprecedented" numbers of new registrations, while others received "tens of thousands" of applications in the final week.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The UK Government said that, if a simple majority of the vote was in favour of independence, then 'Scotland would become an independent country after a process of negotiations'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] If the majority opposed independence, Scotland would remain part of the United Kingdom.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Further powers would be devolved to the Scottish Parliament as a result of the Scotland Act 2012.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission prepared an information leaflet which confirmed that the UK and Scottish governments had reached agreement on these points.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Cameron said in May 2014 that he believed that the referendum would be 'irreversible and binding'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the week before the referendum, both sides said they would abide by the result.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond said that it was a 'once in a generation' event, citing the precedent of the two devolution referendums in 1979 and 1997.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the event of a majority for Yes, the Scottish Government had proposed an independence date of 24 March 2016.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was suggested that, after negotiations concluded, the UK Parliament would legislate for Scottish independence to take place on the date that had been negotiated.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A report by a UK House of Lords committee published in May 2014 said that the UK could opt to delay the independence date.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, as part of a European Union (EU) member state, Scottish farmers received £583 million in subsidy payments from the EU under the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Annual CAP payments are made to the UK, which then determines how much to allocate to each of the devolved administrations, including Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the last CAP agreement, farmers in the UK qualified for additional convergence payments because Scottish farmers received a lower average single farm payment per hectare, mainly due to the mountainous terrain in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence therefore believed that an independent Scotland would receive greater agricultural subsidies as an independent state.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Opponents of independence believed that Scottish farmers benefited from the Union because the UK was one of the larger EU member states, and therefore had a greater say in CAP negotiations.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] They also questioned whether an independent Scotland would immediately receive full subsidy payments from the EU, as recent new member states had their subsidies phased in.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the independence referendum, the UK had some opt-outs from EU policies.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] One was the opt-out from the Schengen Area, meaning there were full passport checks for travellers from other EU countries except the Republic of Ireland, which was part of a Common Travel Area (CTA) with the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that an independent Scotland would remain outside the Schengen Area and remain inside the CTA, ensuring that no passport controls would be needed at the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon commented that an independent Scotland would negotiate with the EU to have the same visa arrangements as the UK has.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Carmichael, the Secretary of State for Scotland, said in January 2014 that it would make sense for Scotland to be in the CTA, but it would have to operate similar immigration policies to the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This position was supported by Home Secretary Theresa May, who said in March 2014 that passport checks should be introduced if Scotland adopted a looser immigration policy.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Conservative MP Richard Bacon said there would be "no reason" for border controls to be implemented.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the white paper *Scotland's Future*, the Scottish government pledged to expand childcare provision in an independent Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The paper stated that this policy would cost £700 million, but that this would be financed by increased tax revenue from an additional 100,000 women returning to work.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In March 2014, the National Day Nurseries Association said that the plan could not be implemented unless greater funding was provided by local authorities to private nurseries.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Scottish Parliament Information Centre questioned the economic benefit of the policy, pointing out that there were only 64,000 mothers of children aged between 1 and 5 who were economically inactive.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that all British citizens who had been born in Scotland would automatically become Scottish citizens on the date of independence, regardless of whether or not they were then living in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] British citizens "habitually resident" in Scotland would also be considered Scottish citizens, even if they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Every person who would automatically be considered a Scottish citizen would be able to opt-out of Scottish citizenship provided they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] UK Home Secretary Theresa May said the future policies of an independent Scottish government would affect whether Scottish citizens would be allowed to retain British citizenship.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] An analysis paper published by the UK government in January 2014 stated that it was likely that Scots would be able to hold dual citizenship; however, the duality was considered for all other countries, not specifically to the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The possibility of holding dual UK–Scotland citizenships could be subject to the "proof of affinity".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A YouGov poll in early September showed 25 per cent of the electorate believed MI5 was working with the British government to block independence, with many voters so fearful that the marks made by the pencils provided in polling stations would be tampered with that they brought their own pens.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP said that there was a defence underspend of 'at least £7.4 billion' between 2002 and 2012 in Scotland and that independence would allow the Scottish government to correct this imbalance.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In its white paper, the Scottish government planned that an independent Scotland would have a total of 15,000 regular and 5,000 reserve personnel across land, air and maritime forces by 2026.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In July 2013, the SNP proposed that there would be a £2.5 billion annual military budget in an independent Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons Defence Select Committee said that the £2.5bn budget was too low.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Andrew Murrison, UK Minister for International Security Strategy agreed and said it was 'risible' for the SNP to suggest it could create an independent force by 'salami-slicing' from current British armed forces units.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons defence committee also stated that Scottish independence would have a negative effect on its industry, while the UK government said it would not be willing to build warships in a foreign country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The chief executive of Thales, one of Britain's largest defence suppliers, said that if Scotland became independent that this might raise questions about continued investment from his firm.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Royal United Services Institute said in 2012 that an independent Scotland could set up a Scottish Defence Force, comparable in size and strength to those of other small European states like Denmark, Norway, and Ireland, at an annual cost of £1.8 billion.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Dorcha Lee, a former colonel in the Irish Army, said that Scotland could eschew forming an army based on inherited resources from the British Army and instead follow an Irish model of a limited self-defence force.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the referendum, the Trident nuclear missile system was based at Coulport weapons depot and naval base of Faslane in the Firth of Clyde area.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP objected to having nuclear weapons on Scottish territory, but British military leaders said that there was no alternative site for the missiles.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In April 2014, several British military leaders co-signed a letter stating that forcing Trident to leave Scottish waters would place the UK nuclear deterrent in jeopardy.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] *Nowhere to Go*, a report by Scottish CND, concluded that the removal of Trident from Scotland would force unilateral nuclear disarmament by the United Kingdom, as the weapons would have no viable alternative base.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Royal United Services Institute said that relocating Trident would be 'very difficult, but not impossible' and estimated it would take about 10 years and create an additional cost of around £3 billion.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] According to a seminar hosted by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, that the Royal Navy would have to consider a range of alternatives, including disarmament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A 2013 Scotland Institute report suggested a future Scottish government could be convinced to lease the Faslane nuclear base to the rest of the UK, in order to maintain good diplomatic relations and expedite NATO entry negotiations.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] SNP policy had historically been that an independent Scotland should not seek to obtain membership in NATO, but this was dropped after a vote by party members in 2012.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] MSPs John Finnie and Jean Urquhart resigned from the SNP over this policy change.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party and Scottish Socialist Party continued their opposition to NATO membership.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP position that Trident nuclear weapons should be removed from Scotland but that it should hold NATO membership was criticised by Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Patrick Harvie, co-convenor of the Scottish Green Party.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Malcolm Chalmers of the Royal United Services Institute said that 'pragmatists' in the SNP accepted that NATO membership would likely involve a long-term basing deal, enabling the UK to keep Trident on the Clyde.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was disputed by Mariot Leslie, a former UK permanent representative to NATO, who said that NATO would not want to disrupt its arrangements by excluding Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A UK government paper on security said that Police Scotland would lose access to the UK intelligence apparatus, including MI5, SIS, and GCHQ, and that an independent Scottish state would need to build security infrastructure.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Theresa May commented that an independent Scotland would have access to less security capability, but would not necessarily face a reduced threat.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] May also indicated that the British government would block Scotland from joining the Five Eyes intelligence-sharing alliance until Scotland had built up its own spying and intelligence infrastructure and was able to offer the alliance a "unique contribution".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Allan Burnett, former head of intelligence with Strathclyde Police and Scotland's counter-terrorism coordinator until 2010, said that 'an independent Scotland would face less of a threat, intelligence institutions will be readily created, and allies will remain allies'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Baroness Ramsay, a Labour peer and former case officer with MI6, said that the Scottish government's stance on intelligence was 'extremely naïve' and that it was "not going to be as simple as they think".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon said that Scotland would create a security service like MI5 to work alongside police and tackle terrorism, cyber-attacks and serious organised crime, and that creating an external intelligence agency would remain an option.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government and pro-independence campaigners said there was a democratic deficit in Scotland because the UK was a unitary state without a codified constitution.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP also called the unelected House of Lords an 'affront to democracy'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The 'democratic deficit' label has sometimes been used to refer to the period between the 1979 and 1997 UK general elections, during which the Labour Party held a majority of Scottish seats but the Conservative Party governed the whole of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in September 2013 that instances such as this amounted to a lack of democracy, and that 'people who live and work in Scotland are the people most likely to make the right choices for Scotland'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Menzies Campbell wrote in April 2014 that any democratic deficit had been addressed by creating the devolved Scottish Parliament, and that 'Scotland and the Scottish have enjoyed influence beyond our size or reasonable expectation' within the British government and the wider political system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Conservative MP Daniel Kawczynski said in 2009 that the UK's asymmetric devolution had created a democratic deficit for England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was commonly known as the West Lothian question, which cited the anomaly whereby English MPs could not vote on affairs devolved to Scotland but Scottish MPs could vote on the equivalent subjects in England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Kawczynski also pointed out that the average number of voters in a parliamentary constituency was larger in England than in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the campaign, each of the three main UK parties conducted reviews of the UK constitution, with each recommending that more powers should devolve to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On the morning before a televised debate between Alex Salmond and Alistair Darling, Better Together published a joint statement.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Co-signed by the three main UK party leaders (David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg), it committed to granting Scotland increased power over domestic taxes and parts of the social security system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Boris Johnson, the Conservative mayor of London, said he opposed giving the Scottish Parliament greater fiscal powers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the second televised debate, Salmond challenged Darling to specify which additional powers that could help create greater employment in Scotland would be granted if there was a 'no' vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During a visit to Scotland later that week, David Cameron promised more powers 'soon'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 8 September, former Prime Minister Gordon Brown suggested a timetable for the additional powers to be implemented in the event of a 'no' vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He proposed that work on a new Scotland Act would begin immediately after the referendum, resulting in the publication of a white paper by the end of November 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Two days before the referendum, the three main UK party leaders publicly pledged to introduce 'extensive new powers' by the timetable suggested and that the Barnett formula of public funding would continue.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A principal issue in the referendum was the economy.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Weir Group, one of the largest private companies based in Scotland, commissioned a study by Oxford Economics into the potential economic effects of Scottish independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It found that Weir would pay more corporation tax, despite the Scottish government's proposal to cut the rate of corporation tax, due to it no longer being able to offset losses in Scotland against profits in the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It also stated that independence would result in additional costs and complexity in the operation of business pension schemes.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report found that 70% of all Scottish exports are sold to the rest of the UK, which it said would particularly affect the financial services sector.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Standard Life, one of the Scottish financial sector's largest businesses, said in February 2014 that it had started registering companies in England in case it had to relocate some of its operations there.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In February 2014, the *Financial Times* noted that Scotland's per capita GDP was bigger than that of France when a geographic share of oil and gas was taken into account, and still bigger than that of Italy when it was not.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] As of April 2014, Scotland had a similar rate of unemployment to the UK average (6.6%) and a lower fiscal deficit (including as a percentage of GDP).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scotland performed better than the UK average in securing new Foreign Direct Investment in 2012–13 (measured by the number of projects), although not as well as Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] GDP growth during 2013 was lower in Scotland than in the rest of the UK, although this was partly due to an industrial dispute at the Grangemouth Refinery.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Deutsche Bank issued a report in the week before the referendum in which David Folkerts-Landau, the bank's chief economist, concluded: 'While it may sound simple and costless for a nation to exit a 300-year-old union, nothing could be further from the truth'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Folkerts-Landau said the economic prospects after a 'yes' vote were 'incomprehensible', and cited Winston Churchill's 1925 Gold Standard decision and the actions of America's Federal Reserve that triggered the Great Depression of the 1930s as mistakes of a similar magnitude.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Swiss financial services company UBS supported Deutsche Bank's position.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence said that Scotland had not realised its full economic potential because it was subject to the same economic policy as the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation published a report stating that UK economic policy had become 'overwhelmingly geared to helping London, meaning Scotland and other UK regions suffer from being denied the specific, local policies they need'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Later in January 2014, Colin Fox said that Scotland is 'penalised by an economic model biased towards the South East of England'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In November 2013, Chic Brodie said that Scotland was deprived of economic benefit in the 1980s after the Ministry of Defence blocked oil exploration off the West of Scotland, ostensibly to avoid interference with the UK's nuclear weapons arsenal.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Treasury issued a report on 20 May 2013 which said that Scotland's banking systems would be too big to ensure depositor compensation in the event of a bank failure.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report indicated that Scottish banks would have assets worth 1,254% of GDP, which was more than Cyprus and Iceland before the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It suggested Scottish taxpayers would each have £65,000 of potential liabilities during a hypothetical bailout in Scotland, versus £30,000 as part of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Economists including Andrew Hughes Hallett, Professor of Economics at St Andrews University, rejected the idea that Scotland would have to underwrite these liabilities alone.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He observed that banks operating in more than one country can be given a joint bailout by multiple governments.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In this way, France, Belgium, and the Netherlands collectively bailed out Fortis Bank and the Dexia Bank.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The American Federal Reserve System lent more than $1 trillion to British banks, including $446 billion to the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), because they had operations in the United States.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Robert Peston reported in March 2014 that RBS and Lloyds Banking Group might be forced to relocate their head offices from Edinburgh to London in case of Scottish independence, due to a European law brought in after the 1991 collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Financial groups including RBS, Lloyds, Clydesdale Bank, TSB, and Tesco Bank later announced that they planned to move their registered headquarters from Scotland to England if Scotland voted for independence, although most indicated that they had no immediate intention to transfer any jobs.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Another major economic issue was the currency that an independent Scotland would use.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The principal options were to establish an independent Scottish currency, join the euro, or retain the pound sterling (a form of currency substitution).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Throughout the 1990s and early 2000s, the SNP's policy was that an independent Scotland should adopt the euro, though this was relegated to a long-term rather than short-term goal by the party's 2009 conference.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] There was disagreement over whether Scotland would be required to join the euro if it became an EU member state in its own right.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] All new members are required to commit to joining the single currency, but they must first be party to ERM II for two years.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government argued that this was a *de facto* opt-out from the euro, because EU member states are not obliged to join ERM II.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] For example, the people of Sweden rejected adopting the euro in a 2003 referendum and its government subsequently refused to enter ERM II.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP favoured continued use of sterling in an independent Scotland through a formal currency union with the UK, with the Bank of England setting its interest rates and monetary policy and acting as its central bank.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In June 2012, Alistair Darling said voters in the rest of the UK could choose not to be in a currency union with Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Sir John Major rejected the idea of a currency union, saying it would require the UK to underwrite Scottish debt.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Gordon Brown said the SNP proposal would create a 'colonial relationship' between Scotland and Westminster.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones said in November 2013 that he would seek a veto on a currency union between Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Yes Scotland said that a currency union would benefit both Scotland and the rest of the UK, as Scotland's exports would boost the balance of payments, and consequently strengthen the exchange rate of sterling.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Meanwhile, UK economists and financial experts said the effect on the balance of payments and the exchange rate would be 'largely neutral'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Sterling fell by almost one cent against the US dollar in a day early in September 2014, due to an opinion poll showing a swing towards the Yes campaign.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The *Financial Times* reported a few days later that 'Asset managers, investors and pension savers are moving billions of pounds out of Scotland' because of fears that Scotland would leave the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The newspaper also reported that '"exit clauses" are being inserted into commercial property contracts in Scotland to allow buyers to scrap deals or renegotiate prices if voters opt for independence'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scottish Labour leader Johann Lamont said that any additional transaction costs would fall largely on Scottish companies, costing businesses in Scotland 11 times more than those in England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute of Directors said that any new transaction costs would 'pale in comparison to the financial danger of entering an unstable currency union'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Banking experts said that being the 'junior partner' in a currency arrangement could amount to 'a loss of fiscal autonomy for Scotland' if policy constraints were imposed on the Scottish state.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Angus Armstrong of the National Institute of Economic and Social Research wrote that the implicit constraints on its economic policy would be more restrictive than the explicit ones it faced as part of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in February 2014 that an independent Scotland in a currency union would retain tax and spending powers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Chancellor George Osborne, as well as equivalent post-holders in the two other main UK political parties, rejected the idea of a formal currency union with an independent Scotland in February 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls said the SNP's proposals for a currency union were 'economically incoherent' and that any currency option for an independent Scotland would be 'less advantageous than what we have across the UK today'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] After the three main UK political parties ruled out a formal currency union, the Adam Smith Institute said that the economies of Panama, Ecuador, and El Salvador 'demonstrate that the informal use of another country's currency can foster a healthy financial system and economy'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In September 2014, former European Commissioner Olli Rehn said that an independent Scotland would be unable to meet EU membership requirements if it shared sterling informally, as it would not have an independent central bank.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond disputed this, restating his belief that a sterling currency union would be formed and pledging to create the necessary financial institutions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Socialist Party favoured an independent Scottish currency, pegged to sterling in the short term.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party said that keeping sterling as 'a short term transitional arrangement' should not be ruled out, but also that the Scottish Government should 'keep an open mind about moving towards an independent currency'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In early 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation described retention of the pound as a good transitional arrangement, but recommended the eventual establishment of an independent Scottish currency to 'insulate' Scotland from the UK's 'economic instability'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Other proponents of an independent Scottish currency included Yes Scotland chairman Dennis Canavan and former SNP deputy leader Jim Sillars.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 9 September 2014, Mark Carney, governor of the Bank of England, said that a currency union between an independent Scotland and the remainder of the UK would be 'incompatible with sovereignty'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He added that cross-border ties on tax, spending and banking rules are a prerequisite: 'You only have to look across the continent to look at what happens if you don't have those components in place ...
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At present under devolution, Scotland controls only 7% of our revenues.' Carney's comments received vocal support from Darling and the GMB trade union.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Barnett formula, introduced in the late 1970s, had resulted in higher per-capita public spending in Scotland than England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] If an allocation of North Sea oil revenue based on geography was included, Scotland also produced more per capita tax revenue than the UK average in the years immediately preceding the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute for Fiscal Studies reported in November 2012 that a geographic share of North Sea oil would more than cover the higher public spending, but warned that oil prices are volatile and that they are drawn from a finite resource.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Government Expenditure and Revenue Scotland report for 2012/13 found that North Sea oil revenue had fallen by 41.5% and that Scotland's public spending deficit had increased from £4.6 billion to £8.6 billion.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2012, the Scottish Government's Finance Secretary John Swinney prepared a confidential cabinet briefing paper on the financial impact of Scottish independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that an independent Scotland would face public spending cuts, lower pensions and welfare spending, and high levels of debt.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that Scotland's public finances would be heavily dependent on volatile and declining oil revenues, and suggested that the affordability of the state pension in an independent Scotland would be at risk.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report further warned that the SNP's plans for an oil fund under independence would "require some downward revision in current spending." Swinney's cabinet paper was kept secret before being leaked to the press in 2013, a year after it was drafted.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Darling, the leader of the Better Together campaign opposed to Scottish independence, described the leaked report as a "hammer blow" to the SNP's economic credibility.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A Scottish Government spokesman insisted that the report's findings had been "overtaken by events".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, the UK government published an analysis identifying a 'Union dividend' of £1,400 per year for each person in Scotland, mainly due to the higher level of public spending.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government disputed this analysis, saying that each Scot would be £1,000 better off per year under independence by 2030.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Three economic experts said that both estimates were possible, but they depended on unknown variables such as the division of UK government debt, future North Sea oil revenues, possible spending commitments of an independent Scotland and future productivity gains.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In its analysis, the UK government also estimated setup costs of £1.5 billion (1% of GDP) for establishing an independent state, or possibly £2.7 billion (180 public bodies costing £15 million each).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Patrick Dunleavy of the London School of Economics criticised the UK government's 'ludicrous' use of his research in arriving at the latter figure.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Treasury said that their main figure (£1.5 billion) was based on estimates by Robert Young of Western University.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two of the main unionist parties in Scotland called on the SNP to publish their own estimate of the setup costs of an independent state, but the Scottish government said that an estimate was not possible as the final bill would depend on negotiations with the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Dunleavy estimated immediate setup costs of £200 million in a report commissioned by *The Sunday Post*, with 'total transition costs' of between £600 million and £1,500 million in the first 10 years of independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit rating that an independent Scotland would merit also became a subject of debate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit-rating agency Fitch said in 2012 that it could not give an opinion on what rating Scotland would have, because Scottish finances would largely depend on the result of negotiations between the UK and Scotland and specifically the division of UK assets and liabilities.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research published by Moody's in May 2014 said that an independent Scotland would be given an A rating, comparable with Poland, the Czech Republic and Mexico.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] An A rating would have been two grades below its then rating for the UK, which Moody's said would be unaffected by Scottish independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The UK government controlled most energy issues, although control over planning laws had allowed the Scottish government to prevent the construction of new nuclear power stations in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence wanted to retain a single energy market for the whole of Great Britain after independence, to maintain price stability and support for suppliers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that independence would threaten that single energy market.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister, professor of economics at Aberdeen University, said that although independence would affect the relationship, it was likely that there would be continued English demand for electricity generated in Scotland due to the lack of spare capacity elsewhere.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The second largest supplier of energy in the UK, SSE plc, believed that a single market would be the most likely outcome under independence, although it would require negotiations that may have led to changes to the existing system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Caroline Flint said that independence would mean higher energy bills in Scotland, as its customers would have to pay more to support renewable energy in Scotland, which represented one-third of the UK total.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister said that bills were likely to increase across the whole of Great Britain because renewable schemes and new nuclear power stations in England were receiving higher subsidies than the power plants which were due for closure due to environmental regulations.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that there was a distinction between existing and proposed renewable schemes in that the existing schemes had already been paid for, whereas any new construction required the promise of subsidy from the consumer.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Energy and Climate Change Secretary Ed Davey said Scottish generators would no longer be eligible for UK subsidies, which would increase energy bills for consumers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Approximately 90% of the United Kingdom's North Sea oil fields were located in Scottish territorial waters.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The tax revenue generated from an offshore site was not counted within the nation or region nearest to it, but was instead allocated to the UK Continental Shelf.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The revenue from North Sea oil was used to support current expenditure, and the UK did not create a sovereign oil fund (as in Norway).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP believed that a portion of the revenues should have been invested in a sovereign oil fund.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government, citing industry body Oil and Gas UK, estimated in *Scotland's Future* that there were 24 billion barrels of oil equivalent still to be extracted.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Ian Wood, founder of oil services company Wood Group, said in August 2014 that he believed there were between 15 and 16.5 billion boe and that the impact from declining production would be felt by 2030.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2014, an investigation by industry recruitment website *Oil and Gas People* found that there were extensive oil reserves to the west of the Western Isles and Shetland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The report anticipated that the region would be developed within the next 10 years because of improvements in drilling technology, rig design and surveying.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP advocated that an independent Scotland should become a full member state of the European Union (EU) with some exemptions, such as not having to adopt the euro.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was debate over whether Scotland would be required to reapply for membership and whether it could retain the UK's opt-outs.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The European Commission (EC) offered to provide an opinion to an existing member state on the matter, but the UK government confirmed it would not seek this advice, as it did not want to negotiate the terms of independence in advance of the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was no precedent for an EU member state dividing into two sovereign countries after joining the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence stated that an independent Scotland would become an EU member by treaty amendment under Article 48 of the EU treaties.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that this would not be possible and that an independent Scotland would need to apply for EU membership under Article 49, which would require ratification by each member state.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, Christina McKelvie, Convener of the European and External Relations Committee of the Scottish Parliament, asked Viviane Reding, Vice-President of the European Commission, whether Article 48 would apply.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Reding replied that EU treaties would no longer apply to a territory that secedes from a member state.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She also said that Article 49 would be the route to apply to become a member of the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] José Manuel Barroso, president of the European Commission, said earlier that an independent Scotland would have to apply for EU membership, while the rest of the UK would continue to be a member.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2014, he reiterated that for Scotland to join the EU would be 'extremely difficult, if not impossible'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former prime minister Sir John Major suggested in November 2013 that Scotland would need to reapply for EU membership, but that this would mean overcoming opposition to separatism among other member states.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond cited a letter from Mario Tenreiro of the EC's secretariat general that said it would be legally possible to renegotiate the situation of the UK and Scotland within the EU by unanimous agreement of all member states.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Spain's European Affairs minister reiterated their position two days before the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir David Edward, a former European Court judge, said that the EU institutions and member states would be 'obliged' to start negotiations before independence took effect to decide the future relationship.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He said this would be achieved by agreed amendment of the existing Treaties (Article 48), rather than a new Accession Treaty (Article 49).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Graham Avery, the EC's honorary director-general, agreed with Edward.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Avery wrote a report, published by the European Policy Centre, which said that EU leaders would probably allow Scotland to be part of the EU because of the legal and practical difficulties that would arise from excluding it.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a research paper, Professor Sionaidh Douglas-Scott of Oxford University wrote that the EU law normally takes a 'pragmatic and purposive approach' to issues not already provided for by existing treaties.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, the Republic of Ireland's Minister of European Affairs, Lucinda Creighton, said that if Scotland were to become independent, it 'would have to apply for membership and that can be a lengthy process'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She later clarified those remarks, writing that she 'certainly did not at any stage suggest that Scotland could, should or would be thrown out of the EU'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that Barroso's comments on the legal position had 'no basis in the European treaties'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, David Cameron committed the Conservative Party to a referendum before the end of 2017 on UK membership of the EU if they won the 2015 general election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Legislation for an in/out EU referendum was approved by the House of Commons in November 2013.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Studies showed some divergence in attitudes to the EU in Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, there was a majority for withdrawal in England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland said that the UK government plans for an EU referendum had caused "economic uncertainty" for Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During a CBI Scotland event attended by Cameron, businessman Michael Rake criticised him for creating uncertainty about EU membership.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In response to such criticism, Cameron pointed to examples of inward investment in the UK that he said was not happening in the rest of Europe.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some commentators suggested that the UK leaving the EU could undermine the case for Scottish independence, since free trade, freedom of movement and the absence of border controls between Scotland and England could no longer be assumed.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Responsibility for most aspects of health care was devolved to the Scottish Parliament when it was established in 1999.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government enacted health policies which were different from those in England, such as abolishing charges for prescriptions and elderly personal care.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] NHS Scotland was operationally independent of the NHS in the rest of the United Kingdom since the formation of the NHS in 1948.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence argued that independence was needed because possible reductions in the NHS budget in England would result in reduced funding for Scotland, which would make it difficult to maintain the existing service.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Harry Burns, a former chief medical officer for Scotland, said in July 2014 that he thought independence could be beneficial for public health because it may give people greater control of their lives.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, about 100 medical workers, including surgeons, consultant doctors, GPs, pharmacists, dentists, hospital porters and janitors joined a pro-independence campaign group called "NHS for Yes".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, opponents argued that a subsequent drop in funding to an independent Scottish Government would have a significantly larger effect upon the budget.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Concerns were also raised about the impact on the medical research sector in Scotland from the loss of UK wide research funding.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two days before the referendum, papers indicating "a funding gap of £400–£450m in the next two financial years, 2015–17", for Scotland's NHS, resulting from Scottish government policies, were leaked to the media.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A Scottish government spokesperson commented that the papers were from "part of the regular discussions among NHS leaders to plan for NHS Scotland's future".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents of independence said that being part of the UK was crucial in allowing Scots to obtain specialist treatment elsewhere in the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Although operationally independent, NHS Scotland had reciprocal arrangements in place with the NHS services in the rest of the UK and specialist services were shared.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders, a unionist campaign group, ran a cinema advert which claimed that Scots would find it more difficult to obtain treatment at the Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH), a London facility which provided specialist care for children.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders withdrew the advert after GOSH complained that it had not been consulted about the advert and stated that they had reciprocal health care agreements with numerous countries.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The white paper on independence proposed that an independent Scotland would open around 100 embassies around the world.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Prime Minister David Cameron suggested that an independent Scotland would be "marginalised" at the United Nations, where the UK is a permanent member of the Security Council.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Prime Minister John Major suggested that the UK could lose its permanent seat at the Security Council if Scotland became independent.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Forming a republic was favoured by some pro-independence political parties and organisations, including the Scottish Green Party and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP favoured an independent Scotland continuing to recognise Elizabeth II as Queen of Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Christine Grahame MSP said she believed that party policy was to hold a referendum on the matter, due to a 1997 SNP conference resolution.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some media reports suggested that the announcement on 8 September of the pregnancy of the Duchess of Cambridge with her second child would help pro-union sentiment.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Queen's official position on Scottish independence was neutral.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Just prior to the referendum, Elizabeth II said in a private conversation that she hoped people would "think very carefully about the future".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK State Pensions were managed by the UK government, paying £113.10 per week to a single person who is of state pension age in the 2013/14 tax year.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The state pension age for men was 65, but this was due to rise to 66 in 2020 and 67 by 2028.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research found that an independent Scotland could delay these increases, due to a lower life expectancy.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Scotland's Future* white paper pledged to maintain a state pension at a similar rate to the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former UK Prime Minister Gordon Brown said in April 2014 that Scotland had an above-average share of the public-sector pension bill and concluded that pensions would be protected by sharing risks and resources within the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK government pensions minister Steve Webb said in May 2014 that Scots would be entitled to the current levels of state pension after independence because they had accumulated rights within the existing system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Webb went on to say that there would need to be negotiations between the UK and Scotland as to how these pensions would be paid.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In relation to private pension schemes, a report by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland expressed concern that there were no plans to deal with EU regulations that may affect the funding of cross-border defined benefit schemes.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The EC decided in March 2014 not to relax these regulations, which require cross-border schemes to be fully funded.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scotland hosted the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, less than two months before the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish team won a record number of gold medals, which the writer Alan Bisset said would help give voters more belief and confidence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *Sunday Herald* columnist Ian Bell took an opposing view, saying that sporting success would be unlikely to aid support for independence, due to the lengthy and passionate debate on the subject.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Labour first minister Henry McLeish published a report in May 2014 that found no obvious barriers to an independent Scotland competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] McLeish said that some athletes, particularly those in team sports, may choose to compete for the existing Great Britain team rather than Scotland, as they would be nationals of both states.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Gordon Brown pointed to the 2012 medal count for Great Britain, saying that it showed the success of the union.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish athletes were involved in 13 of the 65 medals won by Great Britain in 2012, but only three of those were won without assistance by athletes from other parts of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Chris Hoy said in May 2013 that it would "take time" for Scottish athletes to "establish themselves in a new training environment", and indicated that the good performance of Scottish athletes in the Great Britain team would not automatically translate into that of an independent Scotland team.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Hoy also said that he believed the lack of facilities and coaching infrastructure in Scotland would have to be addressed by an independent state.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The prospect of an independent Scotland raised questions about the future of the Northern Isles (Orkney and Shetland) and the Western Isles, island groups off the Scottish mainland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some islanders called for separate referendums to be held in the islands on 25 September 2014, one week after the Scottish referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, the Scottish Parliament published an online petition it had received calling for such referendums, which was supported by Shetland MSP Tavish Scott.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The proposed referendums would have asked islanders to choose from three options: that the island group should become an independent country; that it should remain in Scotland; or that (in the event of Scottish independence) it should remain in the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The third option would have implemented a conditional promise made in 2012 by an SNP spokesperson, who said that Orkney and Shetland could remain in the United Kingdom if their "drive for self-determination" was strong enough.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Politicians in the three island groups referred to the Scottish referendum as the most important event in their political history "since the inception of the island councils in 1975".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Angus Campbell, leader of the Western Isles, said that the ongoing constitutional debate offered the "opportunity for the three island councils to secure increased powers for our communities to take decisions which will benefit the economies and the lives of those who live in the islands".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a meeting of the island councils in March 2013, leaders of the three territories discussed their future in the event of Scottish independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] This included whether the islands could demand and achieve autonomous status within either Scotland or the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Among the scenarios proposed were achieving either Crown Dependency status or self-government modelled after the Faroe Islands, in association with either Scotland or the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle, Orkney's council leader, described pursuing Crown Dependency status as the least likely option, as it would threaten funding from the EU, which was essential for local farmers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alasdair Allan, MSP for the Western Isles, said independence could have a positive impact on the isles, as "crofters and farmers could expect a substantial uplift in agricultural and rural development funding via the Common Agricultural Policy if Scotland were an independent member state of the EU".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In July 2013, the Scottish government made the Lerwick Declaration, indicating an interest in devolving power to Scotland's islands.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By November, it had committed to devolving further powers to Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles in the event of independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle called for legislation to that effect to be introduced regardless of the referendum result.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He stated that he did not want such circumstances to arise, "and the best way to avoid this was to vote no in the referendum".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2012–13, Scottish universities received 13.1% of Research Councils UK funding.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alan Trench of University College London said that Scottish universities had received a "hugely disproportionate" level of funding and would no longer be able to access it following independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, suggested that independence would mean Scottish universities losing £210m in research funding.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Institute of Physics in Scotland warned that access to international facilities such as the CERN Large Hadron Collider, the European Space Agency, and European Southern Observatory could require renegotiation by the Scottish government.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It also expressed concerns about research funding from UK charities and the reaction of international companies with Scottish facilities.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government's education secretary, Michael Russell, said that Scotland's universities had a "global reputation" that would continue to attract investment after independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the principal of the University of Aberdeen said that Scottish universities could continue to access UK research funding through a "single research area" that crossed both nations' boundaries.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Bell, professor of economics at the University of Stirling, said that cross-border collaboration might continue, but Scottish universities could still lose their financial advantage.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Roger Cook of the Scotland Institute pointed out that although Scottish universities had received a higher share of Research Councils funding, they were much less dependent on this as a source of funding than their counterparts in England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professors from Scotland's five medical schools wrote an open letter warning that independence would mean Scotland's researcher base being "denied its present ability to win proportionately more grant funding".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Questions were asked whether Scotland, as an economy of a smaller size than the UK, would still support the same level of research activity, and what additional efforts might be required to establish a system of research councils "north of the border".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Jo Shaw, Salvesen chair of European institutions at the University of Edinburgh, noted that in smaller states, relationships between universities and research funders became "cosy", and led to a "corporatist" approach.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the time of the referendum, Students domiciled in Scotland did not pay tuition fees.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Students domiciled in the rest of the UK were charged fees of up to £9,000 per annum by Scottish universities, but those from other EU member states were not charged fees due to EU law.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] If Scotland had become an independent state, students from the rest of the UK would have been in the same position as students from the rest of the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A University of Edinburgh study found that this would cause a loss in funding, which could have squeezed out Scottish students.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It concluded that the EU may allow a quota system for some specialist subjects, such as medicine, where there was a clear need for local students to be trained for particular careers, but that other subjects would not be eligible.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The study also found that their third suggestion would run against the spirit of the Bologna agreement, which aimed to encourage EU student mobility.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government stated in its white paper, *Scotland's Future*, that the present tuition fees arrangement would remain in place in an independent Scotland, as the EU allowed for different fee arrangements in "exceptional circumstances".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Ján Figeľ, a former EU commissioner for education, said in January 2014 that it would be illegal for an independent Scotland to apply a different treatment to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A report by a House of Commons select committee stated that it would cost an independent Scottish government £150 million to provide free tuition to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A group of academics campaigning for independence expressed concern that the present arrangements would not continue if Scotland stayed within the UK, due to public spending cuts in England and the consequential effects of the Barnett formula.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign argued that control of welfare policy would be a major benefit of independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies, independence would "give the opportunity for more radical reform, so that the [welfare] system better reflects the views of the Scottish people".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland and deputy first minister Nicola Sturgeon said the existing welfare system could only be guaranteed by voting for independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO), which represents charities, called for a separate welfare system to be established in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In November 2013, the Scottish government pledged to use the powers of independence to reverse key aspects of the Welfare Reform Act 2012, which was implemented across the UK despite opposition from a majority of Scotland's MPs.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It said it would abolish Universal Credit and the bedroom tax.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP also criticised Rachel Reeves, Labour's shadow secretary of state for work and pensions, for saying that a future UK Labour government would be even tougher on benefits than the Cameron–Clegg coalition government.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour politician Jim Murphy, a former Secretary of State for Scotland, said that he was "fiercely committed" to devolving welfare powers to the Scottish Parliament, but also warned that independence would be disruptive and would not be beneficial.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish Labour's Devolution Commission recommended in March 2014 that some aspects of the welfare state, including housing benefit and attendance allowance, should be devolved.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Feminist economist Ailsa McKay, a supporter of the Radical Independence movement, argued that an independent Scotland should change its welfare system dramatically by offering all its people a basic income.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A number of demonstrations in support of independence were co-ordinated following the announcement of the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally for Scottish Independence in September 2012 drew a crowd of between 5,000 and 10,000 people to Princes Street Gardens.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The event was repeated in September 2013; police estimated that over 8,000 people took part in the march, while organisers and the Scottish Police Federation claimed between 20,000 and 30,000 people took part in the combined march and rally.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally was criticised in both 2012 and 2013 for the involvement of groups like the Scottish Republican Socialist Movement and Vlaamse Volksbeweging.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Five days before the referendum vote, the Orange Order – a Protestant brotherhood – held a major anti-independence march and rally in Edinburgh.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It involved at least 15,000 Orangemen, loyalist bands and supporters from Scotland and across the UK, and was described as the biggest pro-Union demonstration of the campaign up to that date.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A rally for UK unity, organised by the Let's Stay Together campaign, was attended by 5,000 people in London's Trafalgar Square on the Monday preceding the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Similar events were held in London, Bristol, Leeds, Cardiff, Manchester and Belfast on the day before the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Jim Murphy conducted a Scotland-wide tour to campaign for the No side, intending to visit 100 towns and cities in 100 days before the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 28 August he suspended his tour, after being hit by an egg in Kirkcaldy, and it was resumed on 3 September.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Murphy said that he had been subjected to "co-ordinated abuse" from Yes supporters and pointed to evidence of this on social media.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together released footage of events in the tour where he was heckled by members of the public, some of whom called him a "traitor", "parasite", "terrorist" and "quisling".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Cameron said that "there's nothing wrong with a bit of heckling, but throwing things isn't necessarily part of the democratic process".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Salmond pointed out that people had "every entitlement to peaceful protest", but also said that "people shouldn't throw eggs at somebody full stop".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the launch of the Yes Scotland campaign in May 2012, Alex Salmond said that the case for independence would be driven by community activism and "online wizardry".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The not-for-profit and non-partisan *What Scotland Thinks* project tracked poll and survey data, including online activity, during the referendum campaign.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Using data from the Applied Quantitative Methods Network (AQMeN) research centre, the project compiled the social media activity of the two main campaigns, Yes Scotland and Better Together, by monitoring their respective Facebook and Twitter accounts since August 2013.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *What Scotland Thinks* published a report in February 2014 stating that the Yes Scotland campaign was gaining more Facebook likes.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Following the launch of the White Paper on 26 November, the average gap between the two Facebook pages grew from about 8,000 to about 23,000 by February 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Analysis of the campaigns' Twitter accounts showed the gap between the campaigns increased from approximately 8,000 followers in August 2013 to 13,804 followers in February 2014, in favour of Yes Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The project published a further report in June 2014 saying that greater online activity for Yes Scotland had continued.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor Michael Keating said in April 2014 that the pro-independence movement was visibly stronger and fighting a "ground war", while unionist supporters were fighting an "'air war' of facts and figures".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The launch of online celebrity videos from both viewpoints was reported by the media in mid-July 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The "Let's Stay Together" campaign group produced a YouTube video called "'Scotland, you're my best friend'", featuring John Barrowman, Ross Kemp and Eddie Izzard.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A pro-independence video was produced by Yes Scotland and appeared on the campaign's YouTube channel.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Titled "✘ on September 18th #voteYes", the video features 32 people, including David Hayman, Martin Compston and Stuart Braithwaite.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The pro-independence organisation National Collective was identified by the *Independent* newspaper as the initiators of an online hashtag campaign that began in mid-August 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing for the *Independent*, Antonia Molloy said that the previous "#IndyReasons" hashtag campaign served as the inspiration for the "#YesBecause" campaign that was observed on the Twitter, Facebook and Vine social media platforms.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] From 21 August, users were invited to explain their reasons for voting "Yes" and #YesBecause was trending on Twitter after an hour from the launch.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) reported on 22 August that a "#NoBecause" campaign emerged in opposition to the Collective.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Debates over the issue of independence took place on television, in communities, and within universities and societies since the announcement of the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The STV current affairs programme *Scotland Tonight* televised a series of debates: Nicola Sturgeon v Michael Moore, Sturgeon v Anas Sarwar, Sturgeon v Alistair Carmichael and Sturgeon v Johann Lamont.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 21 January 2014, BBC Two Scotland broadcast the first in a series of round-table debates, which was filmed in Greenock and chaired by James Cook.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign repeatedly called for a televised debate between UK Prime Minister David Cameron and First Minister of Scotland Alex Salmond.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] These calls for a one-on-one debate were dismissed by Cameron on the basis that the referendum is "for Scots to decide" and the debate should be "between people in Scotland who want to stay, and people in Scotland who want to go".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Calls for such a debate were also supported by former Prime Minister Gordon Brown who said it would be a "good idea".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together chairman Alistair Darling accused Salmond of "running scared" from debating him instead, although Sturgeon stated in 2013 that a Salmond–Darling debate would take place at some point.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Darling refused a public debate with Yes Scotland chairman Blair Jenkins.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UKIP leader Nigel Farage also challenged Salmond to debate, but Farage was dismissed by an SNP spokeswoman as "an irrelevance in Scotland".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After weeks of negotiation, a debate between Salmond and Darling was arranged.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The programme, titled as *Salmond & Darling: The Debate*, was broadcast by STV on 5 August 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The debate, moderated by Bernard Ponsonby, saw both politicians make opening statements and cross-examine each other before taking questions from the audience.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the end of the clash, they were both given the chance to make a closing speech.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Both campaign groups claimed victory in the debate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A snap poll conducted by ICM stated Darling won the debate by 56% to 44%.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In his analysis of the ICM poll, Professor John Curtice detected little movement either way as a result of the debate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A second debate between Salmond and Darling, titled *Scotland Decides: Salmond versus Darling* was shown on BBC One Scotland (and BBC Two in the rest of the UK) on 25 August, and was hosted by Glenn Campbell.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond was perceived to have won the debate, and a snap poll conducted by ICM Research stated Salmond won the debate by 71% to 29%.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, BBC Scotland chiefs appeared before a Scottish Parliament committee to face questions from MSPs about the broadcaster's coverage.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During that session, BBC Scotland director Ken MacQuarrie disputed the findings of Robertson's study, saying that its conclusions were largely based upon "flawed analysis" and had contained factual errors.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During the latter stages of the campaign there were further allegations by some independence supporters that the BBC – the UK's national broadcaster – was biased against Scottish independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In an interview for the *Sunday Herald*, Alex Salmond said he believed the BBC had been unconsciously biased against independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former BBC journalist Paul Mason commented: "Not since Iraq have I seen BBC News working at propaganda strength like this".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The BBC replied that "Our coverage of the referendum story is fair and impartial in line with the editorial guidelines".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Massie wrote in *The Spectator* that the BBC's coverage was consistent with their attitude towards other government proposals of such magnitude and that it was incumbent upon the Yes campaign to prove its assertions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 29 June, several hundred independence supporters gathered in a demonstration outside BBC Pacific Quay, the main BBC studio in Glasgow, in protest at its alleged bias.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A week before the vote, BBC political editor Nick Robinson said in a news item that Salmond "didn't answer" his questions at a press conference.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Several thousand independence supporters then protested at the BBC Scotland headquarters, accusing the BBC of broadcasting pro-Union "propaganda" and "lies".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *The Independent* reported that the protesters accused Robinson of working "with the Treasury to spread lies about the dangers to business and financial services of an independent Scotland".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alastair Campbell said that the "organised protests" amounted to media censorship "not far off" Vladimir Putin's Russia, telling Twitter users they should "Vote YES for intimidation".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The National Union of Journalists (NUJ) asked people to think about the implications of alleging journalistic bias when its members were only asking difficult questions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Robinson later expressed his "regret" at using the phrase "didn't answer" in his report and criticised the protests.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Speaking after the referendum, Yes Scotland chief executive Blair Jenkins said that he did not believe there was a "systemic bias" against Yes or any "corporate intent to disadvantage the Yes campaign".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In addition to the incidents described above, there were reports of intimidation during the campaign.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A survey of the 133 business leaders who signed a public letter backing the Union reported that half of respondents "said that they had felt intimidated or pressurised by SNP or the Yes campaign as a result of their views".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Daily Telegraph* reported that other businesspeople had been unwilling to express an opinion on the referendum publicly because they were concerned about a loss of business from the SNP-led Scottish government or local government.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The NUJ called for abuse and bullying of its members, which had been led by online attacks, to end, commenting that, "For the duration of the referendum there has been hostility to journalists doing their jobs".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Police Federation stated that criminal acts related to the referendum were few in number and criticised those "suggesting a minority of mindless idiots are representative of anything".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor John Curtice stated in January 2012 that polling showed support for independence at 32%–38% of the Scottish population, which represented a slight decline from 2007, when the SNP had first formed the Scottish government.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By 2012, there had been no poll evidence of majority support for independence, although the share "vehemently opposed to independence" had declined.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to Curtice, the polls were stable during most of 2013, with "no" leading by an average of 17% with a year to go.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Polling expert Nate Silver said in 2013 that the yes campaign had "virtually no chance" of winning the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After the referendum, Silver said that although his prediction had been proven "right" he had done little research beforehand.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The gap narrowed after the release of the Scottish government white paper on independence: an average of five polls in December 2013 and January 2014 gave 39% yes and 61% no, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The polls tightened further after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, George Osborne, stated in February that the UK government was opposed to a currency union; the average yes support increased to 43%, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was little movement in the following months, with the average continuing to show 43% yes and 57% no (excluding don't knows) in July 2014 and August 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In early September, polls indicated that the vote would be closer than had been indicated earlier.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 6 September a YouGov poll gave those in favour 47% versus 45% for those against; excluding those undecided, the figures were 51% and 49%, respectively.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The final polls, taken in the last few days of the campaign, indicated a lead for No of between 4% and 6%.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Soon after polling stations had closed, YouGov released a final poll that had been taken during the day of voting, indicating 46% Yes, 54% No.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing after the referendum, Nate Silver pointed out that the final margin of victory for No was greater than that indicated by the opinion polls.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He suggested that this could have been due to less enthusiastic voters being more pro-Union, which may not have been reflected in the polls.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Stephen Fisher, a sociology professor at Oxford University, noted in a study of other constitutional referendums that pollsters had tended to overestimate the "Yes" option.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2015, a poll carried out by YouGov found a slight majority of support for independence among people born in Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Independence Referendum Bill identified the convener of the Electoral Management Board for Scotland as chief counting officer for the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The chief counting officer, Mary Pitcaithly, was supported by a counting officer in each of the 32 local authority areas of Scotland, who was typically the chief executive for that local authority.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Voting took place between 07:00 and 22:00 BST in "polling places", which included schools, church halls, libraries and community centres.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Those who were still queuing when polls closed were not denied the chance to vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Votes from the 32 local government areas were counted and announced by each area separately.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Results came in during the early hours of 19 September, with the first result being from Clackmannanshire, and the last being from Highland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 55.3% voted against independence, with a turnout of 84.6%.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 28 of the 32 council areas voted "No", although the four areas that voted "Yes" (Dundee, Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and West Dunbartonshire) contained over 20% of the Scottish electorate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The overall turnout of 84.6% was very high for Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Turnout was around 50–60% for elections to the Scottish and UK parliaments in the early 21st century.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The most recent United Kingdom general election with a comparable turnout was in 1950, when 83.9% voted.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The last ballot in the United Kingdom with a higher turnout than 84.6% was in January 1910, when no women and fewer men were allowed to vote (i.e., before universal suffrage applied to UK elections).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Of the 32 areas, East Dunbartonshire had the highest turnout at 91.0%, and Glasgow the lowest at 75.0%.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An academic study, surveying 5,000 Scottish voters soon after the referendum, found that the majority for No was formed by an "unusual alliance" of the very young, average earners, Protestants and women.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The study supported polling evidence that there was a gender gap, but countered beliefs that higher earners had supported No and that younger voters had mostly voted Yes.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to John Curtice, polling evidence indicates that support for independence was highest among those aged in their late 20s and early 30s, with a higher No vote among those aged between 16 and 24.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was an age gap at the referendum, with elderly voters being the most likely to vote against independence and younger voters aged under 55, except for those aged between 16 and 24, generally being more in favour of independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This was picked up by other academics, with data from the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation study from 2012 indicating that the six most deprived local authorities in Scotland returned the highest Yes vote shares at the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This is an incomplete list as not all local authorities counted by ward or constituency.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The constituency results are primarily obtained through local authority breakdowns of the result or the constituency boundaries being co-terminous with the local government district.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day of the referendum, Michael Ashcroft conducted a poll of over 2,000 voters to identify the major reasons for their voting choices.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This poll found that among No voters, more than half (57%) stated the pound sterling was one of the most important factors in their decision.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Among Yes voters, the biggest single motivation was "disaffection with Westminster politics".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron admitted he was "very embarrassed" for revealing the Queen's political view, which she had guarded in her own comments.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Alex Salmond, the Scottish First Minister and leader of the SNP, stated that he accepted the "verdict of the people" and called upon "all Scots to follow suit in accepting the democratic verdict of the people of Scotland".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He called the referendum a "triumph for the democratic process and for participation in politics".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He also resigned as SNP leader and as First Minister, saying that "for me as leader my time is nearly over but for Scotland the campaign continues and the dream shall never die".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Northern Ireland's First Minister Peter Robinson and Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones responded positively to the result.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Robinson was "delighted Scotland has voted to remain in the Union".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was a large international reaction to the results of the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The White House congratulated Scotland on their "full and energetic exercise of democracy".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President Barack Obama noted the "debate, discussion, and passionate yet peaceful deliberations" and welcomed the result, saying he looked forward to "continuing our strong and special relationship with all the people of Great Britain and Northern Ireland".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] John Baird, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada, welcomed the decision and praised the conduct of the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Angela Merkel, the Chancellor of Germany, said that, "We [the German government] have always respected the fact that this referendum was called and that the central government in London agreed to this.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] And now we respect the outcome of it as well".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] When asked how she felt about the result she replied "I will not comment on this but just smile".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We look forward to working with all parties across these islands in the years ahead.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Good Friday Agreement of 1998 is the historic template for harmonious and mutually beneficial development of the totality of relationships among the peoples of these islands.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In particular, it has led to a transformation in relationships between the two great traditions on this island".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We have noted that the UK government has extended concrete promises in this regard.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Facing the result of the referendum, Erna Solberg, Prime Minister of Norway, stated to Norwegian broadcaster NRK she was 'glad' Scotland chose to remain in the union and that Scottish independence could have become challenging for Norway as a neighboring country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Spanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, in a video message, said that the Scottish have avoided serious consequences and "have chosen the most favorable option for everyone; for themselves, for all of Britain, and for the rest of Europe".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Iñigo Urkullu, the President of the Basque Country, stated on the day of the referendum that as the British Government had allowed Scotland to freely decide its own future, the responsibility of the Basque government was to "follow Scotland's footsteps" in securing a similar agreement in Spain.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Artur Mas, President of the Generalitat of Catalonia, described the referendum as a model for a future vote in the Catalonia, and said "What happened in Scotland is not a setback for us, because what we really want in Catalonia is to have the chance to vote".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day after the Scottish referendum, the Catalan parliament voted to hold a "popular consultation" on Catalan independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Spanish government said that such a vote would be unconstitutional, but a referendum was held on 9 November 2014 anyway.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The large majority (80%) voted for Catalonia to be an independent country, although two-thirds of Catalans did not participate in the referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Secretary General of NATO Anders Fogh Rasmussen said that he fully-respected "the choice that the people of Scotland have made".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso said the Scottish vote was good for a "united, open, and stronger Europe".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Ten voters discovered that someone had voted under their names at polling stations in Glasgow, a method of fraud termed 'personation', and this led to an investigation by Police Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] During a BBC results broadcast, Scottish Conservative Party leader Ruth Davidson said that "No" campaigners had been "taking tallies" of postal votes and that those showed that the "No" campaign was in the lead.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This resulted in complaints to the electoral commission because the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 stated that people attending proceedings related to the receipt of postal votes must not attempt to ascertain the outcome or "communicate any information" from that voting.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Electoral Commission, who could not investigate criminal allegations, passed the complaints onto Police Scotland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A formal investigation was subsequently opened, which concluded that there was no criminality.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to official Russian observers, the conditions under which the votes were counted were not up to international standards and that the procedure used made it impossible to check on irregularities.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russia's criticism came just months after the international community had rejected the results of a Kremlin-backed referendum held in the Russian-occupied Ukrainian territory of Crimea.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russian officials said that the strong performance of the Scottish National Party (SNP) at the 2015 general election confirmed their suspicions about the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A petition demanding a second referendum, based on allegations of vote-miscounting, gained more than 70,000 signatures within 24 hours.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In response, Chief Counting Officer Mary Pitcaithly declared that the referendum had been "properly conducted".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An official spokesperson reiterated this point, saying that they were "satisfied that all counts throughout Scotland were properly conducted" and that incidents in the footage could be "easily explained" and were being presented as a "'conspiracy' theory".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the night of 19 September, hundreds of unionists arrived to celebrate the 'No'-vote and some attacked independence supporters who had gathered in George Square, Glasgow.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Many of the unionists waved Union Jacks or loyalist flags and chanted "Rule, Britannia!" Police officers were drafted in to separate the groups but some unionists broke through police lines.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A number of people were reportedly beaten and bottles were thrown.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A press-photographer told *The Scotsman* he saw people being "kicked about" and was forced to flee after being threatened.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By the end of the following month, the police had made 32 arrests in relation to the events.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The violence was condemned by politicians from both the 'Yes'- and 'No'-camps.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the weeks following the referendum, thousands of people joined the Scottish National Party, the Scottish Greens, or the Scottish Socialist Party, which had all campaigned for a 'Yes'-vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The parties claimed that many of the new members were former Scottish Labour Party members.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By 2 October 2014, SNP membership had tripled from 25,000 to 75,000 people, overtaking the Liberal Democrats as the third-largest political party in the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Conservative MP David Mundell said that 80,000 people had signed up to their "Friends of the Union" group during the campaign.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] These people had not necessarily become full members of the Conservative Party because they were not focussed on increasing the number of "card-carrying" members.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, there were calls for greater unity within Scottish unionism and to vote tactically against nationalist candidates.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A grassroots campaign called "Scotland in Union" aimed to encourage tactical voting at the 2015 general election and to publicise the benefits of Scotland being a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Analysis by the Electoral Reform Society prior to the 2015 general election identified some constituencies where tactical voting could succeed, but also pointed out that many voters would find it difficult to support another political party.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Writing after the election, Professor John Curtice said that in only one constituency (Edinburgh South) could it be said that tactical voting succeeded in defeating an SNP candidate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Two days before the referendum, the leaders of the three main UK political parties publicly pledged to devolve "extensive new powers" to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] They also agreed to a timetable proposed by Gordon Brown.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In his speech responding to the referendum results, David Cameron said that an all-party commission, chaired by Lord Smith of Kelvin, would oversee the implementation of the new powers.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron also called for an answer to the West Lothian question, by removing the right of Scottish MPs to vote on legislation relating only to England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This proposal was opposed by Gordon Brown, who signed a petition calling for the additional powers to be devolved without any other conditions being attached.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The proposals were debated at length by the UK and Scottish parliaments.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The bill devolving further powers to Scotland was approved unanimously by the Scottish Parliament in March 2016.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, the SNP took a clear lead over the other parties in Scottish opinion polls.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the 2015 general election, the SNP received 1,454,436 votes, 49.97% of the Scottish vote and 56 out of the 59 Scottish seats contested in the election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Labour lost forty of their forty-one seats and the Liberal Democrats lost ten of their eleven seats – all to the SNP.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The SNP replaced the Liberal Democrats as the third largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] As the Conservatives won an overall majority in the 2015 UK general election, a UK-wide referendum on European Union membership was held in June 2016.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An overall majority of the UK voted to leave the EU (for "Brexit"), while all of Scotland's council areas voted to remain in the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Shortly afterwards, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon announced her intention to prepare legislation for a second independence referendum.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the June 2017 general election, the first major electoral test after the EU referendum, the SNP won 35 of the 59 Scottish seats in the House of Commons.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This represented a drop of 21 seats from 2015, with the Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats all making gains.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Those results were largely reversed in the December 2019 general election, as the SNP won 48 seats and the Conservatives and Labour both made net losses.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] An election for the National Assembly for Wales was held on Thursday 5 May 2016, to elect members (AMs) of the National Assembly for Wales, later known as the Senedd (Welsh Parliament; Welsh: *Senedd Cymru*).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] It was the fifth election for the assembly, the third election taken under the rules of the Government of Wales Act 2006 and the first since the Wales Act 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The governing Labour Party's share of the vote fell by over 7% and 29 Labour AMs were elected, one fewer than in 2011 and two short of an overall majority.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Plaid Cymru became the Assembly's second largest party and the official opposition to the Welsh Government with 12 seats, one more than before.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] 11 Conservative AMs were elected, three fewer than in 2011.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Although they did not win a single constituency, the UK Independence Party (UKIP) had seven members elected through the regional lists vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The Liberal Democrats had only one AM returned, down from five.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The election was held on the same day as elections for the Scottish Parliament, the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Mayor and Assembly of London and in numerous local authorities in England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The by-election for the Westminster seat of Ogmore was also held on the same day.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] This election and elections to the other devolved chambers were delayed by a year from 2015 to 2016 as a result of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] In general elections for the National Assembly for Wales, each voter has two votes in a mixed member system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The first vote is for a candidate to become the Assembly Member for the voter's constituency, elected by the first past the post system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The second vote is for a regional closed party list of candidates.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Additional member seats are allocated from the lists by the d'Hondt method, with constituency results being taken into account in the allocation.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The overall result is approximately proportional.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Previously it was not allowed to stand in both a constituency and a regional list, but this rule was abolished by the Wales Act 2014.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The Act also introduced a ban on dual mandates with the House of Commons: an Assembly Member is no longer allowed also to be an MP.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] British, Irish, Commonwealth and European Union citizens living in Wales aged 18 or over on election day were entitled to vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2016-national-assembly-for-wales-election] 23 of the members elected to the Assembly in the election were not members of the previous Assembly.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] A by-election for the United Kingdom parliamentary constituency of Newport West was held on 4 April 2019, following the death of incumbent Labour Party MP Paul Flynn.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] Labour candidate Ruth Jones held the seat for the party, albeit with a reduced majority.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] In October 2018, the sitting MP Paul Flynn indicated his intention to resign his seat in the imminent future following a worsening of his rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] At the time, Flynn indicated that he would wait for a snap general election in case that allowed him to stand down without triggering a by-election, citing the expense involved in organising and holding one.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] He died on 17 February 2019 following a "long illness".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] Newport West was held by Labour since 1987, when Flynn won the seat from the Conservatives.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The constituency was semi-marginal, with Labour majorities not exceeding 10,000 votes except during the electoral landslide of 1997.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The writ of election was moved in Parliament on 28 February, scheduling the by-election for 4 April 2019.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] UKIP selected its Welsh leader Neil Hamilton.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The Liberal Democrats selected Ryan Jones.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] Also standing were Richard Suchorzewski for the Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party; June Davies for the Renew Party; Ian McLean for the continuing SDP; and candidates for For Britain and the Democrats and Veterans.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The new Brexit Party said it would not be standing.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The recently formed Independent Group also declined to field its own candidate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The election was administered by Newport City Council, with the statement of persons nominated published on 8 March 2019.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] Welsh First Minister Mark Drakeford announced on 12 March that the expected decision on the construction of an M4 relief road around Newport would be delayed due to the purdah rules that had taken effect during the by-election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] Such rules prevented the government from making major policy announcements to avoid unduly influencing an election campaign.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The news was strongly criticised by the Conservative candidate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The national backdrop for the by-election was the continued uncertainty over Brexit during the Brexit negotiations in 2019, with the original planned date for leaving the European Union being postponed and the failure of the House of Commons to agree a way forward.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] The Conservatives were concerned this would adversely affect their vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2019-newport-west-by-election] Paul Flynn was re-elected to an eighth term of office in the 2017 general election, with an increased majority of 5,658 (13.0%) over the Conservative candidate.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] An election for the Senedd (Welsh Parliament; Welsh: *Senedd Cymru*) took place on Thursday 6 May 2021 to elect 60 members to the Senedd.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] It was the sixth devolved general election since the Senedd (formerly the National Assembly for Wales) was established in 1999.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The election was held alongside the Scottish Parliament election, English local elections, London Assembly and mayoral election and the Hartlepool by-election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] It was the first election in which 16- and 17-year-olds and legally resident foreign nationals were allowed to vote in Wales, the largest extension of the franchise in Wales since 1969.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Both changes were a result of the Senedd and Elections (Wales) Act 2020.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] It was also the first election for the legislature under its new name – 'Senedd Cymru' or 'the Welsh Parliament' – and thus this election may be called the "2021 Welsh Parliament election", or "2021 Senedd Cymru election", in preference over the shorter name.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Five parties had Members of the Senedd (MSs, formerly Assembly Members – AMs) elected at the previous election: Welsh Labour, the Welsh Conservatives, Plaid Cymru, the UK Independence Party (UKIP), and the Welsh Liberal Democrats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Seven political parties were represented in the Senedd prior to the election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] These are the five aforementioned parties and two parties that gained MSs who were elected for – and moved from – other political parties.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party gained two MSs who were elected for UKIP in 2016, and Propel (previously the Welsh Nation Party) gained an MS elected for Plaid Cymru in 2016.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The governing Labour Party's share of the constituency vote increased by over 5%, and the regional vote by over 4%, with thirty Labour MSs elected accounting for exactly half of the sixty seats, one more than in 2016 but one short of an overall majority and remaining as the largest party.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Conservatives became the Senedd's second-largest party and the official opposition to the Welsh Government with sixteen MSs elected, five more than their 2016 result.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] This result is the best that the Conservatives managed to achieve since the Senedd was established.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Plaid Cymru slipped down to third place with thirteen MSs elected, one more than in 2016.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Coalition partner, the Liberal Democrats lost their single constituency seat from 2016, but gained a regional list seat, keeping their total of one seat, the same as in 2016.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] UKIP received no seats, down from their seven in the 2016 election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] This included seats later transferred to Abolish the Welsh Assembly, who also received no seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Voter turnout was 46.6%, a record for a Senedd election at the time.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] In elections for the Senedd, using the additional member system, each voter has two votes.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The first vote is for a member for the voter's constituency, elected by the first past the post system.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] In this election the system achieved a broadly proportional result in the North Wales and Mid and West Wales electoral regions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Under the Wales Act 2014, a candidate is allowed to stand in both a constituency and a regional list.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] However, holding a dual mandate with the House of Commons is illegal, meaning a Member of the Senedd cannot also be an MP.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] This was the first election where 16- and 17-year olds could vote, following the enactment of Senedd and Elections (Wales) Act in January 2020.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The registration deadline for voters in this election was 11:59 pm, 19 April 2021.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The 2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom was the last of its kind.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The newly formed Brexit Party came out on top in Wales.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Plaid Cymru, who support full Welsh independence, came second, marking the first time it had beaten Labour in a Wales-wide election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Brexit Party also formed a parliamentary group in the Assembly made up of the four ex-UK Independence Party (UKIP) members, led by Mark Reckless.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] A snap general election in the United Kingdom was held on 12 December 2019.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Welsh Labour suffered an 8% drop in their vote, losing all their seats in North Wales, except for Alyn and Deeside.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Labour ended up losing six parliamentary seats to the Welsh Conservatives in Boris Johnson's landslide victory.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] These seats included Bridgend, which has been represented on the assembly level by former First Minister of Wales Carwyn Jones since the 1999 election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Conservatives also picked up Brecon and Radnorshire from the Welsh Liberal Democrats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom left the European Union.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] This followed a referendum on the matter in which Wales narrowly voted to leave the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] South Wales has been highlighted by many as evidence that Brexit cut across traditional party allegiances, as the area typically votes overwhelmingly for Labour.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The band of eight local authorities covering the Valleys area from Swansea in the west to Torfaen in the east, plus the coastal city of Newport, all voted in favour of Brexit, and all are represented in the House of Commons by Labour MPs, all of whom wished to remain in the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Plaid Cymru campaigned for a Remain vote in the 2016 referendum on the UK's membership of the EU.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Plaid Cymru later supported, during the final stages of Brexit process, a second referendum on the matter.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Plaid argued that there should be a referendum on Welsh independence after Brexit, so that Wales could apply for EU membership.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] A June 2020 YouGov/ITV Cymru poll concluded that 25% were in favour of independence and 54% opposed.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The same poll found that 22% of respondents wanted no devolution in Wales, and that 25% were for abolition of the Senedd, with 48% opposed to abolition.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] A follow-up YouGov poll in August 2020 concluded that support for Welsh independence had risen to 32%.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 17 May 2020, Health Minister Vaughan Gething told ITV Wales it was "possible" that the election might not be allowed to happen, because of the uncertainty of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The First Minister Mark Drakeford announced on 29 June 2020 that a group with representatives from all of the main parties would look at the arrangements that might have to be in place for the election if COVID-19 restrictions are still required.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] It would look at campaigning and voting, gathering "views over the summer so that by September, any changes the group feels would be beneficial can be considered and taken forward".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Wales Electoral Coordination Board said on 5 January 2021 that counting of Senedd election votes cannot be done overnight because of COVID restrictions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Welsh Government introduced a bill under emergency legislation, Welsh Elections (Coronavirus) Bill, in January 2021.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] It gives the Llywydd (presiding officer) the power to delay the election (with the recommendation of date by the First Minister and consent of two-thirds of the Senedd) by up to six months if the Coronavirus pandemic would make the elections unsafe.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The bill was passed on the 10 February 2021 with powers also to introduce early voting and more flexibility with proxy voting.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 9 March 2021 in a joint British Governments statement ministers said that there will be safety measures in place for May's elections.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] They encouraged voters to take their own pens or pencils and reconfirmed their aim for elections being conducted on the 6 May 2021.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] In the three-week review on the 12 March 2021 the First Minister said that the threshold for postponing the election hasn't currently been met.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Drakeford also said that leafleting (not door knocking) will be able to start from 15 March.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] During the pandemic, the Welsh government messaging and laws have been distinct from the UK government's actions in England; this has made the Welsh public more conscious about devolution.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Welsh government only allowed businesses access to the Economic Resilience Fund devolved to them by Westminster if they officially recognised a trade union which could recruit in their workplaces.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Welsh government announced a two-week lockdown to reduce the prevalence of the virus – called a "firebreak" – in line with the other devolved administrations and distinct from the UK government's lockdown in England.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 11 December 2020, Plaid Cymru announced that they would hold a referendum on Welsh independence within five years if they won a majority.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Some observers also believed they would have requested a Welsh independence referendum in exchange for supporting a minority government.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Despite being a unionist party, Labour selected three candidates who supported independence.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 3 February 2021, UKIP leader Neil Hamilton stated that the party would pledge to deliver a referendum on the devolved administrations in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] He later told BBC Radio Wales: "UKIP had its founding principle in getting out of the European Union and now we've done that we can concentrate on reintegrating the United Kingdom...
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 7 March 2021, the Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party announced that it would be running candidates in all constituencies in the election, and also said that it would run candidates on the regional list.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 6 April, BBC News reported that Gareth Bennett would not stand for Abolish, with Bennett coming to a mutual agreement with the party to stand as an independent in Cynon Valley whilst still remaining supportive of the party, a decision which left Mark Reckless as the party's only MS.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] On 16 April, it was reported that of the 70,000 16 and 17-year-olds eligible to vote, less than 9,000 were currently registered in six counties, according to figures collected by the Election Reform Society (ERS).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The deadline to register to vote was Monday 19 April 2021.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Figures later compiled by the BBC suggested around 46% of eligible people in this age group were registered to vote by the deadline.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Labour, Plaid Cymru, Conservatives, Liberal Democrats and Reform UK stood in all 40 constituencies and all five regional ballots.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Five other parties contested all five regions and at least one constituency: Abolish the Welsh Assembly (23 constituencies), UKIP (14 constituencies), Gwlad (14 constituencies), Welsh Green Party (13 constituencies) and Propel (11 constituencies).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Llais Gwynedd and Socialist Party of Great Britain stood in Dwyfor Meirionnydd and Cardiff Central respectively.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Neither party stood in any regional races.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Two parties contested some of the regions and at least one constituency: Freedom Alliance (3 regions and 13 constituencies) and No More Lockdowns (two regions and one constituency).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The five remaining seats were occupied by those independent of political parties.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Some parties opted to only contest the regional lists.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Two parties – Communist Party of Great Britain and TUSC – contested all five electoral regions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The Welsh Christian Party and the Workers Party of Britain both stood in only one region.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic, campaigning took into account health issues.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Restrictions were placed on the ability of campaigners to carry out door-to-door campaigning.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Campaign rallies were not possible, which affected the impact of candidates who normally do well at these events.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Mark Drakeford was criticised for publishing a leaflet in the English language, without a bilingual one.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Joel Williams, Conservative candidate for Cardiff North, got the name of his own constituency wrong on a campaign leaflet.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Dwyfor Meirionydd Conservative candidate, Charlie Evans, had to apologise for a tweet praising Llyn Tryweryn, the lake which was created to provide water for Liverpool, immortalised with the slogan Cofiwch Dryweryn.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] After the death of Prince Philip on 9 April 2021, all of the main political parties suspended campaigning as a mark of respect.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Labour and Plaid Cymru restarted their campaigns three days later.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] NB: MSs in office (i.e. incumbents) before the election are bolded.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] According to the National Assembly for Wales (Representation of the People) Order 1999, "party lists" may include from one to twelve candidates.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] They are elected "in the order that they are included on that list (starting with the highest)".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The list below only shows the first ranks.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Elected candidates are highlighted with party colours.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] The constituency vote is shown in lighter lines, while the regional vote is shown in darker lines.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Below are listed all the constituencies which require a swing of less than 10% from the 2016 result to change hands.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] This election saw the second highest turnout for a Senedd election, with 46.6% of eligible Welsh voters casting their ballot.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] There were, however, also noticeable differences in turnout in certain constituencies, with 52% of registered voters voting in Dwyfor Meirionnydd and just 35% doing so in Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] Dr Jac Larner, a politics lecturer at Cardiff University and an investigator for the Welsh election survey, said that the two largest factors in determining voter turnout between constituencies were their socio-economic make-up and the competitiveness of the seat.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] "Basically, people with higher levels of formal education, people who own houses, people with more wealth essentially, are more likely to turn up to vote," he told BBC News.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] "Straight away, as you compare Cardiff North to Merthyr Tydfil, you see big differences there.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2021-senedd-election] However, we also know there's a pretty strong relationship between how competitive a constituency is and turnout.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-powys-county-council-election] The **2022 Powys Council election** took place on 5 May 2022 to elect 68 members to Powys County Council.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-powys-county-council-election] On the same day, elections were held to the other 21 local authorities and to community councils in Wales as part of the 2022 Welsh local elections.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-powys-county-council-election] The previous Powys all-council election took place in May 2017 and future elections will take place every five years.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-powys-county-council-election] On 25 May 2022, Labour and the Liberal Democrats announced that they had agreed a deal to run the council, meaning Powys would be led by party political groups for the first time since its creation.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Local elections in Wales were held on 5 May 2022 to elect members to the twenty-two local authorities.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] They were held alongside other local elections in the United Kingdom.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The previous elections were held in 2017.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The Welsh Conservatives lost over a third of their seats and their majority on Monmouthshire County Council.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Plaid Cymru won outright control of four councils, which was the highest number in the party's history, however their overall number of councillors elected decreased.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] In the local elections in 2017, 1,271 seats were elected.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Welsh Labour won 468 seats, independent candidates won 309 seats, Plaid Cymru won 208 seats, the Welsh Conservatives won 184 seats, and the Welsh Liberal Democrats won 63 seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Other parties including the Wales Green Party won 22 seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The 2022 Welsh local elections were initially scheduled for 2021, to give councillors a four-year term, but they were delayed to 2022 to avoid clashing with the 2021 Senedd election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The 2021 Local Government and Elections (Wales) Act permanently changed the term length for councillors from four years to five years.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Ahead of the 2022 elections, eleven of the twenty-two councils in Wales were under no overall control with no single party holding more than half of the seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Labour controlled seven councils, Independents controlled two councils, and the Conservatives and Plaid Cymru each controlled one council.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] To have been able to vote in the 2022 local elections in Wales a person must be aged 16 or over on the day of the election (also called "polling day"), have been registered to vote by the morning of the 14 April 2022, registered at an address in Wales, and not be legally excluded from voting.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The deadline for applications to vote by post was 19 April 2022, of which a request must have been put in writing.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] For this election, councils in Wales use first-past-the-post voting (FPTP) in single-member wards and block voting in multi-member wards.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] For the next election in 2027, councils will choose whether to conduct elections under FPTP or the single transferable vote, due to changes in legislation in Wales.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Elections were held for all councillors in all 22 local authorities, all of which were conducted under new boundaries.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] These boundary changes mean a number of seats have been redrawn and the total number of councillors in Wales will fall from 1,254 to 1,233, a decrease of 21.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] 2,436 candidates sought election to 1,231 seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The Conservatives lost 86 councillors and lost control of the one council which they administered, Monmouthshire.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Though Plaid Cymru lost a small amount of councillors, they consolidated and gained three councils.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The Liberal Democrats became the largest party in Powys council.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] The Wales Green Party gained 8 councillors across 7 councils.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Propel gained one councillor in Cardiff.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/2022-welsh-local-elections] Whilst Labour gained two councils and lost one, they gained 66 councillors across the country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The **Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party** (Welsh: *Plaid Diddymu Cynulliad Cymru*), or in Wales, simply **Abolish**, is a registered single issue political party in Wales.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] It stands in opposition to devolution and campaigns for the abolition of the Senedd (Welsh Parliament; Welsh: *Senedd Cymru*), formerly known as the "National Assembly for Wales", the devolved legislature of Wales.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Abolish advocates for devolved powers to be returned to the Secretary of State for Wales in the UK government and to the UK parliament at Westminster.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Abolish was first registered with the Electoral Commission in July 2015.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] It was de-registered in November 2020 because former leader David Bevan failed to renew its registration, but was then re-registered two months later.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The party has not had a candidate elected to the Senedd, but it gained two members in 2019 and 2020 through defections from the UK Independence Party (UKIP), along with one council member in Powys.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] It lost both of its Senedd seats in the 2021 Senedd election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party was formally registered with the Electoral Commission in July 2015 and was publicly launched in November 2015.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Its sole stated aim is the abolition of the Senedd, formerly known as the National Assembly for Wales.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The party nominated candidates for each of the regional lists in the 2016 Assembly elections, winning 4.4% of the regional vote and returned no seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] It did not contest any constituency seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Former UKIP leadership candidate Richard Suchorzewski stood in the 2019 Newport West by-election, the first time the party had nominated a candidate for a Westminster seat.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Suchorzewski stated that his main aim was to raise awareness of the party's message.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] He campaigned on the single issue of the Welsh Assembly, claiming it was "a waste of money" and "an unnecessary tier of politics".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] He finished in 8th place out of 11 candidates, with 0.9% of the vote.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Suchorzewski had previously stood for the Conservative Party and then for UKIP, standing for leadership of UKIP in 2006 and losing to Nigel Farage.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The deputy chair of the Welsh Conservatives, Lee Canning, defected to the party in November 2019, claiming that his former party were not doing enough to maintain the unity of the UK.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The party said it hoped Canning would stand "in a key target seat" in the 2021 Senedd election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] In May 2020, Powys councillor Claire Mills quit the Welsh Conservatives and joined the party for similar reasons, becoming the party's first representative in Welsh local government.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Richard Suchorzewski became the new leader of the party in June 2020.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Later in the same month Gareth Bennett, the former leader of the UKIP Senedd group and Independent MS, joined the party along with former Brexit Party parliamentary candidates Cameron Edwards and Richard Taylor.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] In October 2020, a second member of the Senedd, Mark Reckless, joined the party.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Reckless, who was previously the leader of the Brexit Party in Wales (and prior to that a member of UKIP, and before that a Conservative MP), stated, "we surveyed all the [Brexit] party's registered supporters to ask what they wanted for the future.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Two thirds of them wanted Abolish and an end to devolution.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] So, I am joining the Abolish The Assembly Party to help give those opposed to devolution a proper voice in Welsh politics".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] In November 2020, the Electoral Commission removed the party from the register of political parties.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The party's former leader, David Bevan, had fallen out with the party and did not renew the party's registration.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Instead, he submitted a rival Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party for registration with himself as the leader, claiming this party would be fielding candidates in the next Senedd election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] A spokesman for the original party was quoted opposing the registration, warning Bevan against "stealing the party like a thief in the night".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] This was resolved when the Electoral Commission, in January 2021, rejected the registration of the second party saying, "We have rejected the second application on the basis that when a party is deregistered, its name is protected for a period of time by law.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] In January 2021, Abolish was reinstated on the Electoral Register by the Electoral Commission.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Suchorzewski said he "[looked] forward to naming candidates to stand for Abolish in the Welsh Assembly/Senedd elections due on 6th May – or later if it's postponed due to the other parties running scared and delaying the election as far into the future as possible.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] On 7 March 2021, Abolish announced that it would be running candidates in all constituencies for the 2021 Senedd election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] It also said that it would run candidates on the regional list.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] On 6 April, one month before election day, it was announced that 10 of the party's candidates had dropped out of the election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] This included one of its two MSs, Gareth Bennett, who left to stand as an independent; the reasons for this decision were unspecified.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Richard Suchorzewski was asked during the 24 April 2021 edition of BBC Politics Wales on whether 'Wales was a country'.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Appearing to struggle to answer the question, he stated, "I don't understand the premise behind that question.... quite frankly" but confirmed that Wales was a country.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The interviewer, BBC journalist James Williams, then asked what other countries there are that don't have a parliament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Suchorzewski paused then explained that he didn't understand the point of the question.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] He went on to explain that Wales voted for an Assembly, not a Parliament.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] At the election, Abolish received 18,149 constituency votes and 41,399 regional votes (3.7% of the vote), a drop from its performance in 2016, and failed to win any seats.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] There was a believable option to vote for abolishing the whole thing, that has died on its arse.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] That will change the nature of the discussions.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] A few weeks ago, there was a real possibility that the Abolish the Assembly was going to do well.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The Conservatives would then react by being more in favour in abolish.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] I think that this election and the results on who has won and who has been destroyed should be noted as an important moment in Welsh politics".
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] At the 2022 Welsh local elections, only one candidate stood for Abolish, Stuart Field in the Rhoose Ward of Vale of Glamorgan.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] He received 430 votes but was not elected.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Claire Mills, who had joined Abolish, was re-elected as an independent in the 2022 Powys County Council election.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] In the 2024 United Kingdom general election, the party stood three candidates.
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Stuart Field in the Vale of Glamorgan received 669 votes (1.5% of the vote).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Paul Ashton in Wrexham received 480 votes (1.2% of the vote).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] Jonathan Harrington contested the Brecon, Radnor, and Cwm Tawe constituency, securing 372 votes (0.8% of the vote).
[src:abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party/abolish-the-welsh-assembly-party] The party published its manifesto for the 2021 Senedd election in April 2021.
